emails.subject: üéâ Here are the resources you requested
From Client to Customer: How a Private Credit COO Thinks About AI
emails.body:
View this post on the web at https://cashandcarried.substack.com/p/from-client-to-customer-how-a-private

Cash and Carried‚Äôs first interview of the year, and its first long form piece ever - with Omar Hassan [ https://substack.com/redirect/dbaad5cc-ca33-458a-98df-eda501cdaab4?j=eyJ1IjoiNXZmeXByIn0.McNV8o2DlmmyS6C076LNFFfWD2xVnU1eV3nZgmD2JTU ], CFO & COO of Cloverlay [ https://substack.com/redirect/59182da8-2167-4afd-8756-f490ab124e78?j=eyJ1IjoiNXZmeXByIn0.McNV8o2DlmmyS6C076LNFFfWD2xVnU1eV3nZgmD2JTU ]. I hope you enjoy reading it as much as Omar and I enjoyed the conversation.
There have been obvious and perceptible changes in the world of investment management with the arrival of AI. Even as some of them are clearly visible (and further, clearly transformative) they hardly receive warranted attention.
Among them is a new cadre of empowered buyers, who have always been ever-present in the decision-making calculus of private fund managers: CFOs and COOs.
To be blunt, while AI has transformed the ability to do work, it has made the administration associated with its implementation and adoption much more difficult. 
That is, technology never comes with a playbook on how it should be used, only the fact that it must be used. Its most confident originators are excellent in touting this inevitability, and the torrent of compulsion to use it creates much of the confusion we see in operating teams today.
Further, and as such, the absolute emergence of AI and the overwhelming flood of AI solutions for the endless array of manual human activity has sharpened the need for pivotal decision-making from these buyers.
Somehow‚Äîperhaps unknowingly and unwillingly‚Äîthey were given the enormous task of evaluating the quality of that flood, ensuring an appropriate analysis and implementation, and further expected to do so confidently and efficiently, alongside and in addition to their traditional work.
These professionals are astute observers to the blunderbuss sanguinity of this era‚Äôs greatest technological innovation. At once they are also keenly aware of the thing left to utter abandon by AI‚Äôs greatest champions, the human touch, now a common retroactive marketing gambit many AI companies employ as they run up against the stormy realities of implementation and adoption.
Could there be a more obvious admission than this oblique promotional pivot that technology was neither the complete answer nor the primary one to the most pressing challenges in high finance?
On these matters, I recently had the honored pleasure of speaking to one of the industry‚Äôs sharpest voices: Omar Hassan, CFO and COO of the esoteric, captivating investment manager, Cloverlay.
As the first fever of excitement around AI began to cool, we found ourselves drawn toward weightier questions. Less about what the technology could do, and more about what kind of future it was arranging for us, one in which its presence would be as unavoidable as it was ordinary.
The Esoteric Play
Cloverla
[TRUNCATED]

Hi Matthew,
For the budget testing, I‚Äôm tracking two numbers side by side to see how well revenue is converting into cash. These numbers are Invoices booked (accrual) and Cash collected (cash basis).
I‚Äôm including collected during the period even if it relates to prior invoices since budget is funded by cash, not invoice dates. Also, payments from Clio sync to QBO as Undeposited Funds, so they‚Äôre counted as collected even if not yet in the bank (which means regardless of deposit timing). Once deposits are cleared, bank balances will naturally align.
This month, collections were $18,341.62, slightly behind the $20.8k target (88.2%), with $2,811.99 in pending A/R affecting next month. Please refer to the attached report.
I‚Äôll include this in the monthly report‚Äîlet me know your thoughts.
Regards,

FINTRAC‚Äôs contribution recognized
-----------------------------------------------------------------

FINTRAC‚Äôs financial intelligence was recognized in an investigation on a syndicated mortgage investment fraud conducted by the Royal Canadian Mounted Police Toronto Integrated Market Enforcement Team. As part of this multi-year investigation, 2 individuals have each been charged with fraud over $5,000 under the _Criminal Code_.

With the financial transaction reports received from Canadian businesses across the country, FINTRAC is providing valuable assistance to law enforcement and national security investigations.

News release: Jawad Rathore and Vincenzo Petrozza convicted and sentenced in Fortress syndicated mortgage investment fraud: https://rcmp.ca/en/news/2026/02/4349996

FINTRAC is an independent federal government agency, operating at arm‚Äôs length from police, law enforcement and national security agencies. Its mandate is to receive, analyze, assess and, where appropriate, disclose information to assist in the detection, prevention and deterrence of money laundering, terrorist activity financing, sanctions evasion and threats to the security of Canada.

emails.subject: Item IDs as Business Reference Numbers
emails.body:
Many SharePoint solutions rely on reference numbers to identify requests, cases, or records. Using unique identifiers as business reference numbers is a simple and reliable approach that avoids complex logic. With the right configuration, item IDs can become meaningful identifiers users recognize and trust.

Ultimate Forms makes it easy to generate user-friendly reference numbers. These can appear on forms, views, emails, and printed documents. You can format, prefix, and display these IDs consistently without custom code or external automation. This helps teams standardize how records are referenced across processes.

This approach works especially well for real-world scenarios like service requests, help desk tickets, purchase orders, and approvals. Users immediately see a clear reference number they can quote in conversations and emails. At the same time, administrators benefit from a fast, low-maintenance solution built directly into SharePoint.

Read more in our blog

From 2005 and onwards, Infowise has been a leading provider of forms and automation for Microsoft SharePoint.

Our Ultimate Forms is a all-in-one platform that enables everyone to easily create business solutions in SharePoint without a single line of code, on premises and in the cloud.

Contact Us |

Bottomline- Fireblocks is for digital asset custody/settlement with connected partners ; Elliptic for AML/KYT on stablecoin movements once on chain and finally Notabene for Travel Rule obligations only comes into play if and when the stablecoin is transferred to another VASP requiring Travel Rule Compliance. Another important point to be noted for the payment flow - is that Stream Money will need to integrate with local on/off ramp providers that could handle local fiat, compliance and conversion infrastructure.
Fiat to stablecoin conversions are globally treated as internal asset issuance, therefore *Travel Rule controls* *are applied only* when stablecoins are transferred  between VASPs whilst AML, transaction monitoring applies throughout the flow lifecycle.

Useful portal- may help our team to produce the payment flows - https://docs.formance.com/modules/ledger/example-implementations/stablecoin-operations

emails.subject: Re: Corporate Law Firm
emails.body:
Please let me know any advice you can give me what is right thing to do.
Thank you

On Feb 5, 2026, at 9:17‚ÄØPM, marjan banisaeed <mbanisaeed@hotmail.com> wrote:

Ôªø
Hello
We did the 70,000 franchise fee as payment for the franchise. While we where looking for a site his Growing minds became for sale and the owner of the franchise said it would be good to take Growing minds and change it to Uptown Montessori under the franchise name. I believed him and he did all the disclosure and discover on his end. The Supervisor was running the day to day operations and was told I needed to keep her and the staff they had. A week after we toke over we she demanded a big raise from 60k a year 5 days a week to almost 70k a year only working 4 days a week. She was holding all the information that ran the business and I was informed to take her deal and then find a way to get her out rhe door in a few months. Right now I do not feel welcome their and I do not want to even show up. I know on paper it's my business but to me it feels like it's hers not mine
Marjan



Sent from Outlook<http://aka.ms/weboutlook>

________________________________
From: Matthew Levine <matthew@levinelegal.ca>
Sent: February 5, 2026 11:09 AM
To: marjan banisaeed <mbanisaeed@hotmail.com>
Subject: Re: Corporate Law Firm

Hi Marjan

Good day. I have the FDD, thank you.

At a preliminary level, I have questions about how the transaction was structured, particularly in relation to the franchise agreement that was entered into and the fee that was paid. To start with, can you confirm whether a $70,000 initial franchise fee was paid, and whether you were given an explanation at the time for why the transaction was treated as a new franchise rather than a transfer or change of control?

Before I can assess whether there is a legal issue to be examined, it would be helpful to make sure I understand the situation from your perspective. In particular:

  *   What concern or issue prompted you to reach out now?

  *   Who was responsible for day-to-day management of the business at the time of the transaction, and how was that role described to you?

  *   Were you told that any individual‚Äôs continued involvement was expected or required when the deal was completed?

The reason I ask is that issues involving disclosure and transaction structure are treated differently from operational or personnel disputes, and I want to be clear on the factual background.

Once I have that context, we can discuss whether there is a legal issue worth pursuing and what the appropriate next steps might be.

Best regards



Matthew AJ Levine

Barrister & Solicitor

Amidst technological progress, one thing remains the same: people are constantly looking for answers, solutions, products, and connections. And, today, they do this by searching, streaming, scrolling, and shopping .
This is happening at an immense scale on Google platforms. According to a survey with Ipsos, 83% of global consumers report using Google and/or YouTube on a daily basis, which is significantly higher than any other online platforms.Because Google has this activity at a scale no one else does, Google AI has an unparalleled ability to understand customer intent.

With that in mind, explore the top digital marketing trends and predictions for 2026 from Google visionaries who can help you show up in the moments that matter.

Stay informed and in control with Mastercard‚Äôs Small Business Navigator. This inclusive digital hub‚Äîopen to all small-business owners across Canada‚Äîoffers access to regional economic insights tailored to your postal code.

This edition of theSpendingPulsereport provides a post-holiday snapshot of consumer spending across each Canadian region. Based on in-store and online transactions across all payment types, the report breaks down sector-specificbehaviourto help you understand how consumers are spending in your area after the holiday season.

With this data at your fingertips,you‚Äôllbe better equipped to make confident, informed decisions that support your business and your community

Sign up to receive the spending pulse and start exploring your regional insights today.

emails.body:
Automation fails when ownership and sequence are unclear. This session explains why.

Your Legalboards Webinar Invite

Hi Matthew,

Automation is everywhere in legal right now.

But most firms automate work before it‚Äôs clear who owns it, what happens next, or where that work actually lives.

That‚Äôs how automation turns into noise instead of relief.

I‚Äôm hosting a short Legalboards Academy session to walk through this in a practical way.

*Before You Automate*
*The three things every law firm must fix first*

This is not a tool demo.
It‚Äôs about how work actually moves inside small and mid sized firms.

emails.subject: Re: Corporate Law Firm
emails.body:
Hello
We did the 70,000 franchise fee as payment for the franchise. While we where looking for a site his Growing minds became for sale and the owner of the franchise said it would be good to take Growing minds and change it to Uptown Montessori under the franchise name. I believed him and he did all the disclosure and discover on his end. The Supervisor was running the day to day operations and was told I needed to keep her and the staff they had. A week after we toke over we she demanded a big raise from 60k a year 5 days a week to almost 70k a year only working 4 days a week. She was holding all the information that ran the business and I was informed to take her deal and then find a way to get her out rhe door in a few months. Right now I do not feel welcome their and I do not want to even show up. I know on paper it's my business but to me it feels like it's hers not mine
Marjan



Sent from Outlook<http://aka.ms/weboutlook>

________________________________
From: Matthew Levine <matthew@levinelegal.ca>
Sent: February 5, 2026 11:09 AM
To: marjan banisaeed <mbanisaeed@hotmail.com>
Subject: Re: Corporate Law Firm

Hi Marjan

Good day. I have the FDD, thank you.

At a preliminary level, I have questions about how the transaction was structured, particularly in relation to the franchise agreement that was entered into and the fee that was paid. To start with, can you confirm whether a $70,000 initial franchise fee was paid, and whether you were given an explanation at the time for why the transaction was treated as a new franchise rather than a transfer or change of control?

Before I can assess whether there is a legal issue to be examined, it would be helpful to make sure I understand the situation from your perspective. In particular:

  *   What concern or issue prompted you to reach out now?

  *   Who was responsible for day-to-day management of the business at the time of the transaction, and how was that role described to you?

  *   Were you told that any individual‚Äôs continued involvement was expected or required when the deal was completed?

The reason I ask is that issues involving disclosure and transaction structure are treated differently from operational or personnel disputes, and I want to be clear on the factual background.

Once I have that context, we can discuss whether there is a legal issue worth pursuing and what the appropriate next steps might be.

Best regards



Matthew AJ Levine

Barrister & Solicitor

Pls let me know!



Matthew AJ Levine

FINTRAC announces administrative monetary penalties in the money services business sector
-----------------------------------------------------------------

FINTRAC announced today that it has imposed 2 administrative monetary penalties in the money services business sector, for non-compliance with Part 1 of the _Proceeds of Crime (Money Laundering) and Terrorist Financing Act_ and associated Regulations.

**News releases:**
‚Ä¢ FINTRAC imposes an administrative monetary penalty on Commerciale I.C. ‚Äì Pacific Inc.: https://fintrac-canafe.canada.ca/new-neuf/nr/2026-02-05-eng
‚Ä¢ FINTRAC imposes an administrative monetary penalty on TreasureMeta Corporation: https://fintrac-canafe.canada.ca/new-neuf/nr/2026-02-05-1-eng

**Public notices:**
‚Ä¢ Administrative monetary penalty on Commerciale I.C. ‚Äì Pacific Inc.: https://fintrac-canafe.canada.ca/pen/amps/pen-2026-02-05-eng
‚Ä¢ Administrative monetary penalty on TreasureMeta Corporation: https://fintrac-canafe.canada.ca/pen/amps/pen-2026-02-05-1-eng

FINTRAC is an independent federal government agency, operating at arm‚Äôs length from police, law enforcement and national security agencies. Its mandate is to receive, analyze, assess and, where appropriate, disclose information to assist in the detection, prevention and deterrence of money laundering, terrorist activity financing, sanctions evasion and threats to the security of Canada.

emails.body:
Hi Matthew - stream (Legal and Compliance),

You have a new mention from the STREAM.MONEY workspace (https://stream-is-the-word.slack.com/x-p7320791585378-7681668790805-10444911402180/team).

---

mpdm-tulika.d--matthew--hbedi-1
View in the archives: https://stream-is-the-word.slack.com/x-p7320791585378-7681668790805-10444911402180/archives/C0A9SGN72AU/p1770219044084909

Matthew - stream (Legal and Compliance) (10:30 AM, February 4th)

I'm reluctant to declare that SnowCap is holding client funds, but do recognize that it may be necessary.

Tulika - stream (Legal and Compliance) (10:41 AM, February 4th)

The business model , payment flows/ processing as discussed with Harry suggests the firm will hold client funds therefore bringing SnowCap into the scope of Safeguarding client funds. I assume if we say "Yes" against the qs- Holding client funds will drill down to follow up questions and supporting documents. Loud guess :smile:Can we stick to "No" for the RPAA regn subject to *current status* and later declare that firm is going to hold client funds and provide the supporting docs?

Lets pick up on our call this afternoon.

Against 7.1.1 we have mentioned - Funds are moved through payment networks, and Snowcap *does not take custody or control of end-user funds at any point during the process.* 
Having said Yes to the above will require review revision for the existing draft, finalised answer to other sections.

emails.subject: Order -Ref#02042026
Follow Up and Next Steps
emails.body:
Hi Matthew,

Just following up briefly on my note from Monday. Thank you again for your message, I really appreciate the transparency.
I completely understand, and I‚Äôm very glad to hear that you‚Äôd like to find a way for us to work together.

I also wanted to emphasize that I would be very happy to get started right away with whatever hours you have available initially. My main priority is the opportunity to begin working with you, learn the practice, and contribute as things ramp up.

Your suggestion to touch base again in a couple of weeks makes perfect sense, and once the joint venture is finalized and workflow becomes clearer, we can certainly revisit what a more consistent weekly structure might look like at that time.

I also wanted to mention that I‚Äôm currently in touch with a few individuals and business contacts who may be seeking legal support in the near term, and I would be very happy to explore opportunities to bring additional work into the firm as we get started.

Whenever you have a moment, I‚Äôd be happy to connect briefly by phone, but I‚Äôm also very comfortable moving forward by email if easier.

Thank you again. I‚Äôm very excited about the possibility of working together.

Warm regards,

Laura Hinton

emails.subject: Fwd: 601 Yonge Lease with legal review
emails.body:
Good morning, Matthew -
I don‚Äôt expect you to be able to jump on anything I send immediately (haha), but just a friendly note to make sure the below didn‚Äôt slip through the cracks. Thank you for your partnership and everything you‚Äôve done for me so far! Hope you can help with this. 
:)
Chris 

> Begin forwarded message:
> 
> From: Chris Roop <roop.christopher@gmail.com>
> Subject: Re: 601 Yonge Lease with legal review
> Date: February 3, 2026 at 12:22:20‚ÄØPM EST
> To: Matthew Levine <matthew@levinelegal.ca>
> 
> Hi Matthew-
> As mentioned, I sent lease to lender (TD) for final review before sharing with LL. Seems they want us to go much further on the two clauses marked as problematic as related to CSBFP program. I asked for exact clarity on what needs to come out and have pasted response below. I feel weird striking it myself without running through you. Can you please have a look, let me know if it makes sense (no choice, it seems), then strike as part of final redline. 
> I will then do my best to summarize all changes and share with LL. Fingers crossed, ugh. Stressful!
> Thank you. Note from bank here:
> 
> Good morning Chris,
> 
> I hope you are well. 
> 
> Thank you for your continued support throughout this process.
> 
> Regarding the lease, I wanted to discuss two specific clauses that present challenges for our agreement:
> 
> - Section 3.4 ‚Äì Leasehold Improvements: The clause states, "All Leasehold Improvements shall immediately upon installation become the absolute property of the Landlord, free and clear of any liens or encumbrances." The following needs to be removed: the entire section 3.4 (a, b, c, d). We need to reference the property address in the General Security Agreement, and this clause prevents us from doing so.
> 
> - Section 8.2 ‚Äì No Financing by Tenant of Leasehold Improvements: The clause states, "The Tenant shall not create any lien, mortgage, charge, conditional sale agreement or other encumbrance in respect of its Leasehold Improvements." Removing this clause would allow us to secure the leaseholds, which is necessary for our agreement.
> 
> You are requesting financing on the leasehold improvements, but these clauses prevent you from doing so. 
> 
> Thank you for your attention to these matters. If you have any questions or need further clarification, please let me know. I look forward to working together on this.
> 
> Kind Regards,
>  
> Tisanth Thanabalasingam
> Remote Account Manager, Small Business (Remote Strategy) | TD  Business Banking 
> 
>> On Jan 30, 2026, at 4:33‚ÄØPM, Matthew Levine <matthew@levinelegal.ca> wrote:
>> 
>> Hi Chris
>> 
>> Attached is consolidated redline and clean copy. Under the notices, you should put your address where you want to receive business mail. Please keep me posted.
>> 
>> Best regards
>> Matthew
>> 
>> 
>> Matthew AJ Levine
>> 
>> Barrister & Solicitor
>>

emails.subject: Expand your reach ‚Äî get your Replit App on mobile app stores
emails.body:
Take Your App to Mobile Devices


 Ready to reach millions of mobile users? Learn how to transform your Replit 
project into a native mobile app for iOS and Android.


 <https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mTm_dCF53qk>‚Ää

Create your mobile app:


 * Watch ‚Äî create a mobile app from your Replit project 
<https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mTm_dCF53qk>: Step-by-step tutorial for 
converting your web app
 * Transform your existing code into a mobile-friendly format
 * Add native mobile features and functionality
 * Test your app on virtual devices before submission‚Ää

Publish to app stores:


 * Watch ‚Äî publish your mobile app to app stores 
<https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wLQusAwfjdY>: Complete guide to the submission 
process
 * Navigate Apple App Store requirements and review guidelines
 * Submit your app to Google Play Store efficiently
 * Set up app store listings that attract downloads‚Ää

Mobile app best practices:


 * Design Responsively: Ensure your app looks great on various screen sizes
 * Optimize Performance: Mobile users expect fast, smooth experiences
 * Implement Push Notifications: Keep users engaged and returning
 * Consider Offline Mode: Allow core features to work without internet
 * Simplify Navigation: Mobile interfaces need intuitive, finger-friendly 
designs‚Ää

Submission checklist:


 *  Create compelling app icons and screenshots
 * Write clear, keyword-rich descriptions
 * Set up developer accounts on both platforms
 * Prepare privacy policies and terms of service
 * Plan your pricing strategy (free, paid, or freemium)‚Ää

 Expanding to mobile can dramatically increase your user base and open new 
monetization opportunities. Start building your mobile presence today!

Happy Publishing!

Hi Matthew,

You should see improvements now to the transfer protocol, as we tested to
make sure Lexi asks for more context when qualifying callers. She should
also be less prone to being bullied into an immediate transfer by ensuring
details are collected first.  We added conversation pacing so she
doesn't interrupt the person on the other end while they are still speaking
and will only confirm complex spelling.

We tested it multiple times using different scenarios (which I'm sure you
saw in your inbox lol) but it would be great if you could into GHL and test
it as well using web call, and let us know if there is anything else you
find that needs correcting. :)

emails.subject: Re: 601 Yonge Lease with legal review
emails.body:
Hi Matthew-
As mentioned, I sent lease to lender (TD) for final review before sharing with LL. Seems they want us to go much further on the two clauses marked as problematic as related to CSBFP program. I asked for exact clarity on what needs to come out and have pasted response below. I feel weird striking it myself without running through you. Can you please have a look, let me know if it makes sense (no choice, it seems), then strike as part of final redline. 
I will then do my best to summarize all changes and share with LL. Fingers crossed, ugh. Stressful!
Thank you. Note from bank here:

Good morning Chris,

I hope you are well. 

Thank you for your continued support throughout this process.

Regarding the lease, I wanted to discuss two specific clauses that present challenges for our agreement:

- Section 3.4 ‚Äì Leasehold Improvements: The clause states, "All Leasehold Improvements shall immediately upon installation become the absolute property of the Landlord, free and clear of any liens or encumbrances." The following needs to be removed: the entire section 3.4 (a, b, c, d). We need to reference the property address in the General Security Agreement, and this clause prevents us from doing so.

- Section 8.2 ‚Äì No Financing by Tenant of Leasehold Improvements: The clause states, "The Tenant shall not create any lien, mortgage, charge, conditional sale agreement or other encumbrance in respect of its Leasehold Improvements." Removing this clause would allow us to secure the leaseholds, which is necessary for our agreement.

You are requesting financing on the leasehold improvements, but these clauses prevent you from doing so. 

Thank you for your attention to these matters. If you have any questions or need further clarification, please let me know. I look forward to working together on this.

Kind Regards,
 
Tisanth Thanabalasingam
Remote Account Manager, Small Business (Remote Strategy) | TD  Business Banking

Whether you‚Äôre looking to move from your current role or temporarily out of work, searching for the proper contract or permanent position can make even the most seasoned professional feel uncertain. LRO Staffing is here to open doors to opportunities and guide you through the job search process ‚Äì from the initial interview to the signed contract or job offer.

Below is our proven process to ensure the job you take is the one that‚Äôs a better match for you and your goals.

Client Assessment

We conduct a comprehensive overview of the client company‚Äôs requirements to ensure we truly understand the nature of the role and the qualifications necessary to ensure success.

Narrowing our Search & Presenting Top Talent

We build a shortlist of the most suitable candidates by assessing the individuals already registered with LRO Staffing and canvassing the market for other potential candidates. From there, we present a shortlist to the client and each candidate's qualification assessment.

Interviews

We arrange interviews between the client and candidates and conduct reference checks on those selected as finalists.

Negotiation & Follow Up

We work with both parties on remuneration and present the job offer to the successful candidate. In the case of contract assignments, we ensure that you have the support you need while onsite with our clients and we work towards lining up your next role ‚Äì a benefit that is invaluable to most independent contractors.

Maheer Azmat

Ôªø
Hi Maheer


Here is one of the disputes.

Naal is a contractor. he has paid for supplies that are being imported by a canadian company. this canadian company suddenly refuses to deliver unless he pays for shipping.


my idea is

  *   work from existing RFI
  *   generate two lists
     *   what we need before agreeing to act for Naal's business
     *   what we will need before preparing a statement of claim
  *

thanks!







Matthew AJ Levine
Barrister & Solicitor

Na‚Äôal Kullab

We haven't heard back from you since our last mail sent on 5th January 2026.

Manpreet

emails.subject: RE: My Matter: 24-682-00002
Re: hi
emails.body:
Ok I can talk this week.
Just took a 2 second look.  Looks like a potentially great opportunity if
they send you clients.
Yes need to name the relationship -  the term ‚Äúpartner‚Äù is wrong word.
Unless it is actually meant to be a partnership?
Services definition is very vague.  Not sure if the services are legal
services or not?  That needs to be clear and if not, how to ensure no
reliance on legal advice.
The SOW is not attached - No Appendix 1.

I‚Äôve not got experience entering into anything like this so I would seek
legal advice from a senior partner somewhere with actual experience.
Compliance risks could include obvious partnership liability risks but also
advertising and payment compliance.

I never like a deal that agrees to get paid when they get paid and also
gives them full rights to write down your bill or offer discounts or
whatever deal to the client, and no duty to collect promptly.  Need to
flesh out that piece.

More when we chat.

emails.subject: Happy TuBiShvat
emails.body:
Shalom friends,

We wanted to take a moment to wish you all a very happy Tu BiShvat!

Please join us this evening for some learning in honour of the birthday of
the trees. Rabbi Aaron Levy of Makom Downtown Judaism will be speaking to
us about the importance of environmental preservation in Jewish law and
tradition.

This event is *free, online through Zoom*. The link will be sent out to any
last minute registrants at about 5pm. We encourage attendees to donate to
Makom <https://makomto.org/donate/> through this link.

To register for this event please click here <https://bit.ly/TJLS_TuBishvat>
.

See you there!

The TJLS Executive Committee
